# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: rebol-red
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] Carl Sassenrath was born in 1957 to Charles and Carolyn Sassenrath in California.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] His father was a chemical engineer involved in research and development related to petroleum refining, paper production, and air pollution control systems.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] In the late 1960s his family relocated from the San Francisco Bay Area to the small town of Eureka, California.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] From his early childhood Sassenrath was actively involved in electronics, amateur radio, photography, and filmmaking.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] When he was 13, Sassenrath began working for KEET, a PBS public broadcasting television station.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] A year later he became a cameraman for KVIQ (ABC affiliate then) and worked his way up to being technical director and director for news, commercials, and local programming.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] In 1980 Sassenrath graduated from the University of California, Davis with a B.S. in EECS (electrical engineering and computer science).
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] During his studies he became interested in operating systems, parallel processing, programming languages, and neurophysiology.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] He was a teaching assistant for graduate computer language courses and a research assistant in neuroscience and behavioral biology.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] Julius Sassenrath, headed the educational psychology department at UC Davis, and his aunt, Dr.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] Ethel Sassenrath, was one of the original researchers of THC at the California National Primate Research Center.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] During his final year at the university, Sassenrath joined Hewlett-Packard's Computer Systems Division as a member of the Multi-Programming Executive (MPE) file system design group for HP 3000 computers.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] His task was to implement a compiler for a new type of control language called *Outqueue*—a challenge because the language was both descriptive and procedural.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] A year later, Sassenrath became a member of the MPE-IV OS kernel team and later part of the HPE kernel group.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] While at HP Sassenrath became interested in minimizing the high complexity found in most operating systems of that time and set out to formulate his own concepts of a microkernel-based OS.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] He proposed them to HP, but found the large company complacent to the "smaller OS" ideas.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] In late 1981 and early 1982, Sassenrath took an academic leave to do atmospheric physics research for National Science Foundation at Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] Upon returning, Sassenrath reached an agreement with HP to pursue independent research into new areas of computing, including graphical user interfaces and remote procedure call methods of distributed computing.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] Later in 1981, impressed by the new computing ideas being published from Xerox PARC, Sassenrath formed an HP project to develop the modern style of window-based mouse-driven GUIs.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] The project, called *Probus* (for professional business workstation) was created on a prototype Sun Microsystems workstation borrowed from Andy Bechtolsheim while he was at Stanford University.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] Probus clearly demonstrated the power of graphical user interfaces, and the system also incorporated hyperlinks and early distributed computing concepts.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] At HP, Sassenrath was involved with and influenced by a range of HP language projects including Ada, Pascal, Smalltalk, Lisp, Forth, SPL, and a variety of experimental languages.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] In 1982, Carl Sassenrath joined Amiga Computer, Inc., a small startup company in Silicon Valley.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] As *Manager of Operating Systems* he was asked to design a new operating system for the Amiga, an advanced multimedia personal computer system that later became the Amiga.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] As a sophisticated computer for its day (Amiga used 28 DMA channels along with multiple coprocessors), Sassenrath decided to create a true real-time multitasking operating system within a microkernel design.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] This was a novel approach for 1983 when other personal computer operating systems were single tasking such as MS-DOS (1981) and the Macintosh (1984).
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] The Amiga multitasking kernel was also one of the first to implement a microkernel OS methodology based on a real-time message passing (inter-process communication) core known as Exec (for executive) with dynamically loaded libraries and devices as optional modules around the core.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] This design gave the Amiga OS a great extensibility and flexibility within the limited memory capacity of computers in the 1980s.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] Sassenrath later noted that the design came as a necessity of trying to integrate into ROM dozens of internal libraries and devices including graphics, sound, graphical user interface, floppy disk, file systems, and others.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] This dynamic modular method also allowed hundreds of additional modules to be added by external developers over the years.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] After the rerelease of the Amiga after 3 tries in 1985, Sassenrath left Commodore-Amiga to pursue new programming language design ideas when Amiga went bankrupt in 1994.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] In 1986, Sassenrath left Silicon Valley for the mountains of Ukiah valley, 2 hours north of San Francisco.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] From there he founded multimedia technology companies such as Pantaray, American Multimedia, and VideoStream.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] He also implemented the Logo programming language for the Amiga, managed the software OS development for CDTV, one of the first CD-ROM TV set-top boxes, and wrote the OS for Viscorp Ed, one of the first Internet TV set-top boxes.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] In 1996, after watching the growth and development of programming languages like Java, Perl, and Python, Sassenrath decided to publish his own ideas within the world of computer languages.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] The result was REBOL, the *relative expression-based object language*.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] REBOL is intended to be lightweight, and specifically to support efficient distributed computing.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] Sassenrath describes REBOL as a balance between the concepts of context and symbolism, allowing users to create new relationships between symbols and their meanings.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] By doing so, he attempts to merge the concepts of code, data, and metadata.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] Sassenrath considers REBOL experimental because it provides greater control over context than most other programming languages.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] Words can be used to form different grammars in different contexts (called *dialecting*).
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] Sassenrath claims REBOL is the ultimate endpoint for the evolution of markup language methodologies, such as XML.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] In 1998, Sassenrath founded REBOL Technologies, a company he still runs.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] The company has released several versions of REBOL and produced additional products such as REBOL/View, REBOL/Command, REBOL/SDK, and REBOL/IOS.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] Sassenrath implemented REBOL V3.0 and released it to GitHub on December 12, 2012: https://github.com/rebol/r3.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] Since 2010, Sassenrath had worked at Roku, Inc. in product development.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] Sassenrath lives in Ukiah, California, where he grows grapes and makes wine, and is interested in amateur radio, video production, quantum electrodynamics, and boating.
[src:rebol-red/carl-sassenrath] He volunteers with the Television Improvement Association, a community organization that brings free, over-the-air television broadcasts into the Ukiah area.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] A **domain-specific language** (**DSL**) is a computer language specialized to a specific application domain.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] This is in contrast to a general-purpose language (GPL), which is broadly applicable across domains.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] There are a wide variety of DSLs, ranging from widely used languages for common domains, such as HTML for web pages, down to languages used by only one or a few pieces of software, such as MUSH soft code.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] DSLs can be further subdivided by the kind of language, and include domain-specific *markup* languages, domain-specific *modeling* languages (more generally, specification languages), and domain-specific *programming* languages.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Special-purpose computer languages have always existed in the computer age, but the term "domain-specific language" has become more popular due to the rise of domain-specific modeling.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Simpler DSLs, specifically ones used by a single application, are sometimes informally called **mini-languages**.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] For example, Perl was originally developed as a text-processing and glue language, for the same domain as AWK and shell scripts, but was mostly used as a general-purpose programming language later on.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] In contrast, PostScript is a Turing-complete language, and in principle can be used for any task, but in practice is narrowly used as a page description language.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] The design and use of appropriate DSLs is a key part of domain engineering, by using a language suitable to the domain at hand – this may consist of using an existing DSL or GPL, or developing a new DSL.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Language-oriented programming considers the creation of special-purpose languages for expressing problems as standard part of the problem-solving process.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Pragmatically, a DSL may be specialized to a specific problem domain, a specific problem representation technique, a specific solution technique, or other aspects of a domain.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language is created specifically to solve problems in a specific domain and is not intended to be able to solve problems outside of it (although that may be technically possible).
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] In contrast, general-purpose languages are created to solve problems in many domains.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language is somewhere between a tiny programming language and a scripting language, and is often used in a way analogous to a programming library.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] The boundaries between these concepts are quite blurry, much like the boundary between scripting languages and general-purpose languages.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific languages are languages (or often, declared syntaxes or grammars) with very specific goals in design and implementation.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] A domain-specific language can be one of a visual diagramming language, such as those created by the Generic Eclipse Modeling System, programmatic abstractions, such as the Eclipse Modeling Framework, or textual languages.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] For instance, the command line utility grep has a regular expression syntax which matches patterns in lines of text.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] The sed utility defines a syntax for matching and replacing regular expressions.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Often, these tiny languages can be used together inside a shell to perform more complex programming tasks.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] The line between domain-specific languages and scripting languages is somewhat blurred, but domain-specific languages often lack low-level functions for file system access, interprocess control, and other functions that characterize full-featured programming languages, scripting or otherwise.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Further blurring this line, many domain-specific languages have exposed APIs, and can be accessed from other programming languages without breaking the flow of execution or calling a separate process, and can thus operate as programming libraries.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Some domain-specific languages expand over time to include full-featured programming tools, which further complicates the question of whether a language is domain-specific or not.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] In model-driven engineering, many examples of domain-specific languages may be found like Object Constraint Language (OCL), a language for decorating models with assertions or Query/View/Transformation (QVT), a domain-specific transformation language.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] However, languages like Unified Modeling Language (UML) are typically general-purpose modeling languages.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] To summarize, an analogy is useful: a *very little language* is like a knife, which can be used in thousands of different ways, from cutting food to self-defense.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] A *domain-specific language* is like an electric drill: it is a powerful tool with a wide variety of uses, but a specific context, namely, making holes in things.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] A *general purpose language* is a complete workbench, with a variety of tools intended for performing a variety of tasks.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific languages should be used by programmers who, looking at their current workbench, realize they need a better drill and find that a given domain-specific language provides exactly that.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] DSLs implemented via an independent interpreter or compiler are termed *external domain specific languages*.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] A separate category termed *embedded (or internal) domain specific languages* are typically implemented within a host language as a library and tend to be limited to the syntax of the host language, though this depends on host language abilities.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Adopting a domain-specific language approach to software engineering involves both risks and opportunities.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] The well-designed domain-specific language manages to find the proper balance between these.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] GML is a domain-specific language used by GameMaker Studio designed to help novice programmers learn the fundamentals of coding more easily.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] It functions as a blend of several languages, including Delphi, C++, and BASIC.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Most GML functions, once compiled, call runtime functions written in the specific language of the target platform; consequently, their final implementation remains hidden from the user.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] The language's primary goal is to lower the barrier to entry for game development.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] The GameMaker runtime, which manages the main game loop and handles function implementation, allows a simple game to use only a few lines of code instead of thousands.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] ColdFusion's associated scripting language is another example of a domain-specific language for data-driven websites.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] The language is used to weave together languages and services such as Java, .NET, C++, SMS, email, email servers, http, ftp, exchange, directory services, and file systems for use in websites.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] The ColdFusion Markup Language (CFML) includes a set of tags that can be used in ColdFusion pages to interact with data sources, manipulate data, and display output.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] CFML tag syntax is similar to HTML element syntax.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Although the FilterMeister language reproduces a significant portion of the C language and function library, it contains only those features which can be used within the context of Photoshop plug-ins and adds a number of specific features only useful in this specific domain.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] The *Template* feature of MediaWiki is an embedded domain-specific language whose fundamental purpose is to support the creation of page templates and the transclusion (inclusion by reference) of MediaWiki pages into other MediaWiki pages.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] There has been much interest in domain-specific languages to improve the productivity and quality of software engineering.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Domain-specific language could possibly provide a robust set of tools for efficient software engineering.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Such tools are beginning to make their way into the development of critical software systems.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] The Software Cost Reduction Toolkit is an example of this.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] A newer development is language-oriented programming, an integrated software engineering methodology based mainly on creating, optimizing, and using domain-specific languages.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Complementing language-oriented programming, and all other forms of domain-specific languages, are the class of compiler writing tools called metacompilers.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Such compiler is useful for generating parsers and code generators for domain-specific languages, and a metacompiler compiles a domain-specific metalanguage specifically designed for the domain of metaprogramming.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Besides parsing domain-specific languages, metacompilers are useful for generating a wide range of software engineering and analysis tools.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] The meta-compiler methodology is often found in program transformation systems.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Metacompilers that played a significant role in both computer science and the computer industry include META II, and its descendant TreeMeta.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Unreal and Unreal Tournament unveiled a language named UnrealScript.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] This allowed rapid development of modifications relative to the competitor Quake (using the Id Tech 2 engine).
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] The Id Tech engine used standard C code meaning C had to be learned and properly applied, while UnrealScript was optimized for ease of use and efficiency.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Similarly, more recent games have introduced their own specific languages for development.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] One more common example is Lua for scripting.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Various business rules engines have been developed for automating policy and business rules used in both government and private industry.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] ILOG, Oracle Policy Automation, DTRules, Drools and others provide support for DSLs aimed to support various problem domains.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] DTRules goes so far as to define an interface for the use of multiple DSLs within a rule set.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] The purpose of business rules engines is to define a representation of business logic in as human-readable fashion as possible.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] This allows both subject-matter experts and developers to work with and understand the same representation of the business logic.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Most rules engines provide both an approach to simplifying the control structures for business logic (for example, using declarative rules or decision tables) coupled with alternatives to programming syntax in favor of DSLs.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Statistical modelers have developed domain-specific languages such as R (an implementation of the S language), Bugs, Jags, and Stan.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] These languages provide a syntax for describing a Bayesian model and generate a method for solving it using simulation.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Generate object handling and services based on an Interface Description Language for a domain-specific language such as JavaScript for web applications, HTML for documentation, C++ for high-performance code, etc.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] This is done by cross-language frameworks such as Apache Thrift or Google Protocol Buffers.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Gherkin is a language designed to define test cases to check the behavior of software, without specifying how that behavior is implemented.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] It is meant to be read and used by non-technical users using a natural language syntax and a line-oriented design.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] The tests defined with Gherkin must then be implemented in a general programming language.
[src:rebol-red/domain-specific-language] Then, the steps in a Gherkin program acts as a syntax for method invocation accessible to non-developers.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] In computer programming, **homoiconicity** (from the Greek words *homo-* meaning "the same" and *icon* meaning "representation") is an informal property of some programming languages.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] A language is **homoiconic** if a program written in it can be manipulated as data using the language.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] The program's internal representation can thus be inferred just by reading the program itself.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] This property is often summarized by saying that the language treats code as data.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] The informality of the property arises from the fact that, strictly, this applies to almost all programming languages.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] No consensus exists on a precise definition of the property.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] In a homoiconic language, the primary representation of programs is also a data structure in a primitive type of the language itself.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] This makes metaprogramming easier than in a language without this property: reflection in the language (examining the program's entities at runtime) depends on a single, homogeneous structure, and it does not have to handle several different structures that would appear in a complex syntax.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] Homoiconic languages typically include full support of syntactic macros, allowing the programmer to express transformations of programs in a concise way.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] A commonly cited example is Lisp, which was created to allow for easy list manipulations and where the structure is given by S-expressions that take the form of nested lists, and can be manipulated by other Lisp code.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] Other examples are the programming languages Clojure (a contemporary dialect of Lisp), Rebol (also its successor Red), Refal, Prolog, XSLT, and possibly Julia (see the section “Implementation methods” for more details).
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] The researchers implicated in this quote might be neurophysiologist and cybernetician Warren Sturgis McCulloch (note the difference in the surname from the note) and philosopher, logician and mathematician Charles Sanders Peirce.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] Pierce indeed used the term "icon" in his Semiotic Theory.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] According to Peirce, there are three kinds of sign in communication: the icon, the index and the symbol.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] The icon is the simplest representation: an icon physically resembles that which it denotes.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] One advantage of homoiconicity is that extending the language with new concepts typically becomes simpler, as data representing code can be passed between the meta and base layer of the program.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] The abstract syntax tree of a function may be composed and manipulated as a data structure in the meta layer, and then evaluated.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] It can be much easier to understand how to manipulate the code since it can be more easily understood as simple data (since the format of the language itself is as a data format).
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] A typical demonstration of homoiconicity is the meta-circular evaluator.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] All Von Neumann architecture systems, which includes the vast majority of general purpose computers today, can implicitly be described as homoiconic due to the way that raw machine code executes in memory, the data type being bytes in memory.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] However, this feature can also be abstracted to the programming language level.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] Languages such as Lisp and its dialects, such as Scheme, Clojure, and Racket employ S-expressions to achieve homoiconicity, and are considered the "Purest" forms of homoiconicity, as these languages use the same representation for both data and code.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] Other languages provide data structures for easily and efficiently manipulating code.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] Notable examples of this weaker form of homoiconicity include Julia, Nim, and Elixir.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] Lisp uses S-expressions as an external representation for data and code.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] S-expressions can be read with the primitive Lisp function `READ`.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] `READ` returns Lisp data: lists, symbols, numbers, strings.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] The primitive Lisp function `EVAL` uses Lisp code represented as Lisp data, computes side-effects and returns a result.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] The result will be printed by the primitive function `PRINT`, which creates an external S-expression from Lisp data.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] Lisp data, a list using different data types: (sub)lists, symbols, strings and integer numbers.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] The example uses lists, symbols and numbers.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] The operator `:-` separates the head and the body of a clause.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] With `assert/1`* we add it to the existing clauses (add it to the "database"), so we can call it later.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] In other languages we would call it "creating a function during runtime".
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] We can also remove clauses from the database with `abolish/1`, or `retract/1`.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] `call` is analogous to Lisp's `eval` function.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] The concept of treating code as data and the manipulation and evaluation thereof can be demonstrated very neatly in Rebol.
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] (Rebol, unlike Lisp, does not require parentheses to separate expressions).
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] (`repeat` is in fact a built-in function in Rebol and is not a language construct or keyword).
[src:rebol-red/homoiconicity] The block can still be interpreted by using the `do` function provided in Rebol (similar to `eval` in Lisp).
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming can be used to move computations from runtime to compile time, to generate code using compile time computations, and to enable self-modifying code.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] The ability of a programming language to be its own metalanguage allows reflective programming, and is termed *reflection*.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] Reflection is a valuable language feature to facilitate metaprogramming.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming was popular in the 1970s and 1980s using list processing languages such as Lisp.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] Lisp machine hardware gained some notice in the 1980s, and enabled applications that could process code.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] They were often used for artificial intelligence applications.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming enables developers to write programs and develop code that falls under the generic programming paradigm.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] Having the programming language itself as a first-class data type (as in Lisp, Prolog, SNOBOL, or Rebol) is also very useful; this is known as *homoiconicity*.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] Generic programming invokes a metaprogramming facility within a language by allowing one to write code without the concern of specifying data types since they can be supplied as parameters when used.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] Metaprogramming usually works in one of three ways.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] The second approach is dynamic execution of expressions that contain programming commands, often composed from strings, but can also be from other methods using arguments or context, like JavaScript.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] Thus, "programs can write programs." Although both approaches can be used in the same language, most languages tend to lean toward one or the other.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] The third approach is to step outside the language entirely.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] General purpose program transformation systems such as compilers, which accept language descriptions and carry out arbitrary transformations on those languages, are direct implementations of general metaprogramming.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] This allows metaprogramming to be applied to virtually any target language without regard to whether that target language has any metaprogramming abilities of its own.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] One can see this at work with Scheme and how it allows tackling some limits faced in C by using constructs that are part of the Scheme language to extend C.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] Lisp is probably the quintessential language with metaprogramming facilities, both because of its historical precedence and because of the simplicity and power of its metaprogramming.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] In Lisp metaprogramming, the unquote operator (typically a comma) introduces code that is evaluated at program definition time rather than at run time.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] The metaprogramming language is thus identical to the host programming language, and existing Lisp routines can be directly reused for metaprogramming if desired.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] This approach has been implemented in other languages by incorporating an interpreter in the program, which works directly with the program's data.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] There are implementations of this kind for some common high-level languages, such as RemObjects’ Pascal Script for Object Pascal.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] This script (or program) generates a new 993-line program that prints out the numbers 1–992.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] This is only an illustration of how to use code to write more code; it is not the most efficient way to print out a list of numbers.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] Nonetheless, a programmer can write and execute this metaprogram in less than a minute, and will have generated over 1000 lines of code in that amount of time.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] A quine is a special kind of metaprogram that produces its own source code as its output.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] Quines are generally of recreational or theoretical interest only.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] Not all metaprogramming involves generative programming.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] One style of generative approach is to employ domain-specific languages (DSLs).
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] One usage of metaprogramming is to instrument programs in order to do dynamic program analysis.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] Some argue that there is a sharp learning curve to make complete use of metaprogramming features.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] Since metaprogramming gives more flexibility and configurability at runtime, misuse or incorrect use of metaprogramming can result in unwarranted and unexpected errors that can be extremely difficult to debug to an average developer.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] It can introduce risks in the system and make it more vulnerable if not used with care.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] Some of the common problems, which can occur due to wrong use of metaprogramming are inability of the compiler to identify missing configuration parameters, invalid or incorrect data can result in unknown exception or different results.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] Due to this, some believe that only high-skilled developers should work on developing features which exercise metaprogramming in a language or platform and average developers must learn how to use these features as part of convention.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] The IBM/360 and derivatives had powerful macro assembler facilities that were often used to generate complete assembly language programs or sections of programs (for different operating systems for instance).
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] Macros provided with CICS transaction processing system had assembler macros that generated COBOL statements as a pre-processing step.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] Other assemblers, such as MASM, also support macros.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] Use of dependent types allows proving that generated code is never invalid.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] However, this approach is leading-edge and rarely found outside of research programming languages.
[src:rebol-red/metaprogramming] The list of notable metaprogramming systems is maintained at List of program transformation systems.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Douglas Crockford, known for his involvement in the development of JavaScript, has described Rebol as "a more modern language, but with some very similar ideas to Lisp, in that it's all built upon a representation of data which is then executable as programs" and as one of JSON's influences.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Originally, the language and its official implementation were proprietary and closed source, developed by REBOL Technologies.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Following discussion with Lawrence Rosen, the Rebol version 3 interpreter was released under the Apache License 2.0 on December 12, 2012.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Older versions are available in binary form only, and no source code release for them is planned.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Rebol has been used to program Internet applications (both client- and server-side), database applications, utilities, and multimedia applications.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Rebol was initially an acronym for **R**elative **E**xpression **B**ased **O**bject **L**anguage written in all caps.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] To align with modern trends in language naming represented, e.g. by the change replacing historical name *LISP* by *Lisp*, programmers ceased the practice of writing *REBOL* in all caps.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Sassenrath eventually put the naming question to the community debate on his blog.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] In subsequent writing, Sassenrath adopted the convention of writing the language name as *Rebol*.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] First released in 1997, Rebol was designed over a 20-year period by Carl Sassenrath, the architect and primary developer of AmigaOS, based on his study of denotational semantics and using concepts from the programming languages Lisp, Forth, Logo, and Self.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] *REBOL 2*, the interpreter, which became the core of extended interpreter editions, was first released in 1999.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] *REBOL/View* was released in April 2001, adding graphical abilities on the core language.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] *REBOL/IOS*, an extensible collaboration environment built with REBOL was released in August 2001.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] *REBOL/SDK*, providing a choice of kernels to bind against, as well as a preprocessor, was released in December 2002.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] *Rebol 3* [R3], the newest version of the interpreter, had alpha versions released by REBOL Technologies since January 2008.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Since its release as an Apache 2 project in December 2012, it is being developed by the Rebol community.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] One of the Rebol design principles is "to do simple things in simple ways".
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Rebol domain-specific languages, called *dialects*, are micro-languages optimized for a specific purpose.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Dialects can be used to define business rules, graphical user interfaces or sequences of screens during the installation of a program.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Users can define their own dialects, reusing any existing Rebol word and giving it a specific meaning in that dialect.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Dialects are interpreted by functions processing Rebol blocks (or parsing strings) in a specific way.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] An example of Rebol's dialecting abilities can be seen with the word `*return*`.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] In the *data exchange dialect* `*return*` is just a word not having any specific meaning.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] In the *do dialect*, `*return*` is a global variable referring to a native function passing back a function result value.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] In the *visual interface dialect (VID)*, `*return*` is a keyword causing the layout engine to simulate a carriage return, moving the "rendering pen" down to the beginning of the next line.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] A Rebol interpreter with graphical abilities must understand and interpret many dialects.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] The table below lists the most important ones in order of significance.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Rebol syntax is free-form, not requiring specific positioning.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] However, indentation is often used to better convey the structure of the text to human readers.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Syntactic properties of different dialects may differ.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] The common platform for all Rebol dialects is the *data exchange dialect*; other dialects are usually derived from it.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] In addition to being the common platform for all dialects, the *data exchange dialect* is directly used to represent data and metadata, populate data structures, send data over Internet, and save them in data storage.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] In contrast to programming languages like C, the *data exchange dialect* does not consist of declarations, statements, expressions or keywords.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Unlike ALGOL blocks, Rebol blocks are composite values similar to quoted s-expressions in Lisp.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] The fact that code is written in the form of Rebol blocks makes the language homoiconic.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Special characters are allowed in words, so `a+b` is a word unlike `a + b`, which is a sequence of three words separated by spaces.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Comments may appear following the semicolon until the end of the line.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Multi-line comments or comments not ignored by the lexical parser can be written using "ordinary" datatypes like multi-line strings.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Blocks containing domain-specific language can be submitted as arguments to specific *evaluator* functions.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] The most frequently used evaluator is the `do` function.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] It is used by default to interpret the text input to the interpreter console.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] The *do dialect* interpreted by the `do` function, is an expression-oriented sublanguage of the *data exchange dialect*.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] The main semantic unit of the language is the expression.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] In contrast to imperative programming languages descending from ALGOL, the *do dialect* has neither keywords, nor statements.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Words are used as case-insensitive variables.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Like in all dynamically typed languages, variables don't have an associated type, type is associated with values.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] The result, i.e. the evaluation of a word is returned, when a word is encountered by the `do` function.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] The set-word form of a word can be used for assignment.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] While not having statements, assignment, together with functions with side-effects can be used for imperative programming.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Subblocks of the root block evaluate to themselves.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] This property is used to handle data blocks, for structured programming by submitting blocks as arguments to control functions like `if`, `either`, `loop`, etc., and for dialecting, when a block is passed to a specific interpreter function.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] A specific problem worth noting is that composite values, assigned to variables, are not copied.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] To make a copy, the value must be passed to the `copy` function.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] The `do` function normally follows a prefix style of evaluation, where a function processes the arguments that follow it.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] However, infix evaluation using infix operators exists too.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Infix evaluation takes precedence over the prefix evaluation.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] returns 1, since the infix addition takes precedence over the computation of the absolute value.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] When evaluating infix expressions, the order of evaluation is left to right, no operator takes precedence over another.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] returns 20, while an evaluation giving precedence to multiplication would yield 14.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] `Do` usually evaluates arguments before passing them to a function.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] first reads the Wikipedia Rebol page and then passes the result to the `print` function.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Parentheses can be used to change the order of evaluation.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Using prefix notation, the usage of parentheses in expressions can be avoided.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] The simple precedence rules allow writing expressions without consulting a precedence table that would change to reflect inclusion of new operators, and also allow expressions to be changed from prefix to infix notation using simpler methods.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] As a downside, however, they can be a source of mistakes for users accustomed to the conventional notation used by most other languages and tools.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] The `parse` function is preferably used to specify, validate, transform and interpret dialects.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] It does so by matching *parse expressions* at run time.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Actions can be included to be taken during the parsing process as well and the `parse` function can be used to process blocks or strings.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] At the *string parsing* level `parse` must handle the "low level" parsing, taking into account characters and delimiters.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] *Block parsing* is higher level, handling the scanning at the level of Rebol values.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] The parse dialect belongs to the family of grammars represented by the top-down parsing language or the parsing expression grammar (PEG).
[src:rebol-red/rebol] The main similarity is the presence of the *sequence* and *choice* operators all the family members have.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] The official Rebol 2.7.8 implementation is available in several editions (*/Core*, */View*, */Command*, */SDK* and */IOS*).
[src:rebol-red/rebol] Both */Core* and */View* editions are freely redistributable software.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] The runtime environment is stored in a single executable file.
[src:rebol-red/rebol] *Rebol/Core* 2.7.8, the console edition, is about 300 KB and *Rebol/View* 2.7.8, the graphical user interface edition, is about 650 KB in size.
[src:rebol-red/red-programming-language] The implementation choices of Red intend to create a full stack programming language: Red can be used for extremely high-level programming (domain-specific languages (DSLs) and graphical user interfaces (GUIs) and low-level programming (operating systems and device drivers).
[src:rebol-red/red-programming-language] Key to the approach is that the language has two parts: *Red/System* and *Red*.
[src:rebol-red/red-programming-language] Red seeks to remain independent of any other toolchain; it does its own code generation.
[src:rebol-red/red-programming-language] It is therefore possible to cross-compile Red programs from any platform it supports to any other, via a command-line switch.
[src:rebol-red/red-programming-language] Both Red and Red/System are distributed as open-source software under the BSD 3-clause (modified) license.
[src:rebol-red/red-programming-language] The runtime library is distributed under the more permissive Boost Software License.
[src:rebol-red/red-programming-language] As of version 0.6.4 Red includes a garbage collector "the Simple GC".
[src:rebol-red/red-programming-language] Red was introduced in the Netherlands in February 2011 at the *Rebol & Boron conference* by its author Nenad Rakočević.
[src:rebol-red/red-programming-language] In September 2011, the Red programming language was presented to a larger audience during the Software Freedom Day 2011.
[src:rebol-red/red-programming-language] Rakočević is a long-time Rebol developer known as the creator of the Cheyenne HTTP server.
[src:rebol-red/red-programming-language] Red's syntax and semantics are very close to those of Rebol.
[src:rebol-red/red-programming-language] Like Rebol, it strongly supports metaprogramming and domain-specific languages (DSLs) and is therefore an efficient tool for dialecting (creating embedded DSLs).
[src:rebol-red/red-programming-language] Red includes a dialect named Red/System, a C-level language which provides systems programming facilities.
[src:rebol-red/red-programming-language] Red is easy to integrate with other tools and languages as a dynamic-link library (DLL) (libRed) and very lightweight (around 1 MB).
[src:rebol-red/red-programming-language] It is also able to cross-compile to various platforms (see #Cross compiling section below) and create packages for platforms that require them (e.g., .APK on Android).
[src:rebol-red/red-programming-language] Red also includes a fully reactive cross-platform GUI system based on an underlying reactive dataflow engine, a 2D drawing dialect comparable to SVG, compile-time and runtime macro support, and more than 40 standard datatypes.
[src:rebol-red/red-programming-language] Bootstrap phase: Red and Red/System compilers complemented by a Red just-in-time compilation (JIT) compiler, all written in Red.
[src:rebol-red/red-programming-language] (As of 2018, Red applications are 32-bit.
